racil.\n\nLet me trace through:\n- C: methyl carbon\n- n1: aromatic nitrogen (start ring 1)\n- c(=O): aromatic carbon with =O\n- n(C): aromatic nitrogen with methyl\n- c(=O): aromatic carbon with =O\n- c(N): aromatic carbon with NH2 (N is non-aromatic nitrogen with implicit H's)\n- c1: aromatic carbon (close ring 1 to n1)\n\nRing: n1-c(=O)-n(C)-c(=O)-c(N)-c1 (6-membered ring)\n\nThis is a valid SMILES for 5-amino-1,3-dimethyluracil.\n\nBut wait, I should check: is the ring aromatic? In the SMILES, all ring atoms are lowercase (aromatic). For a uracil derivative to be considered aromatic, it needs to satisfy Hückel's rule.\n\nUracil has 6 π-electrons in the ring (from C2=O, C4=O, C5=C6, and the lone pairs on N1 and N3). Wait, the exocyclic =O groups don't contribute to the ring π-system in the same way.\n\nActually, in the Kekulé structure of uracil:\n- C2=O and C4=O are exocyclic\n- C5=C6 is an endocyclic double bond\n- N1 and N3 each contribute one lone pair to the ring\n\nSo the ring π-electrons: 2 (from C5=C6) + 2 (from N1 lone pair) + 2 (from N3 lone pair) = 6 π-electrons. This satisfies Hückel's rule (4n+2, n=1).\n\nSo uracil can be considered aromatic, and the lowercase SMILES is valid.\n\nOK, I'm confident. Let me finalize.\n\nActually, one more thing. I want to make sure the SMILES for N,N-dimethylthioformamide is correct.\n\nN,N-dimethylthioformamide: (CH3)2N-CH=S\n\nSMILES: CN(C)C=S\n\nLet me trace:\n- C: methyl carbon\n- N(C): nitrogen with methyl (the second methyl)\n- C=S: carbon with =S (the thioformyl carbon)\n\nWait, this gives: C-N(C)-C=S\n\nThat's: CH3-N(CH3)-CH=S\n\nWhich is (CH3)2N-CH=S. Correct!\n\nBut I should double-check: is the H on the CH implicit? In SMILES, C=S means a carbon with a double bond to sulfur. The carbon has 2 explicit bonds (to N and to S). For a carbon with 4 valence, it needs 2 more bonds, which would be 2 implicit H's. But CH=S should have only 1 H.\n\nHmm, C=S in SMILES: the carbon has bonds to N and =S (double bond count